g" label="Author's Name" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="true">Brian Schmidt</Author><BodyCopy type="dhtml" label="Body Copy" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="false" Height=""><![CDATA[<p style="margin-top: 0in; margin-right: 0in; margin-bottom: 10pt; margin-left: 0in;"><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: x-small;">On February 29th President Clark held a special interactive discussion for students in the Hart Auditorium about the Learning Model.<span> </span>The principles and process steps of the Learning Model<span style="font-family: minion-pro-1, minion-pro-2, georgia, serif; font-size: 14px; display: inline;"><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: x-small;">&nbsp;</span></span><span style="display: inline;">were discussed and then applied with a case study.</span></span><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: x-small;"><span> </span>The forum was unique from traditional presentation formats in that President Clark roamed the audience to direct student responses.<span> </span>(Learn more about this approach by reading&nbsp;<span style="display: inline;">A Classroom Discussion for 2,400<span style="display: inline;">).</span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin-top: 0in; margin-right: 0in; margin-bottom: 10pt; margin-left: 0in;"><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: x-small;">Since many faculty members were unable to attend, we are posting video segments to show major parts of the forum.<span> </span>Click on the links below to view.</span></p>
